# Build Dispatcher Verb Execution

## Question

The hands half, in joelclaw-observer: the dispatcher classifies
`pane.schedule.due` as a first-class fate (not invoke-pattern matching —
a named kind in dispatch-rules) and executes the verb via herdr in the
observer family session: WAKE = `agent send` + enter to the target (from
the family registry or pane id); SPAWN = new labeled ⏰ pane + `pi
@briefPath`; REVIVE = resolve the loop's continuation prompt (from the
wiki's edition/loops data — read-only) and boot a new ⏰ pane with it.
Every execution writes a decision receipt (verb, scheduleId, late flag,
pane created). Spawned panes are ordinary pi sessions — never gated
roles. Also: a thin observer-family tool (or documented `joelclaw wake`
usage in the charter) so the observer itself can say "wake me in 2h."

## Answer (2026-07-14)

Built in `~/Code/joelhooks/joelclaw-observer` without live-firing the running observer session.

Receipts:

- `dispatch-rules.json` now names `pane.schedule.due` in `paneScheduleKinds`.
- `.pi/extensions/dispatcher/lib.ts` classifies due signals before notify/anomaly/VIP/invoke text matching.
- `.pi/extensions/dispatcher/lib.ts` adds pure schedule parsing/planning, pane-size fallback planning, loop continuation lookup from `joelclaw-wiki/data/editions/*.json`, and versioned executed-schedule state migration.
- `.pi/extensions/dispatcher/index.ts` adds the thin herdr shell: WAKE sends to a resolved target and presses enter; SPAWN creates a labeled `⏰` pane and runs `pi @briefPath`; REVIVE writes a temp prompt file and launches `pi @promptFile`.
- Idempotency state: `~/.joelclaw/observer-dispatcher-executed-schedules.json` via schema v1. Re-delivered executed `scheduleId`s append a `schedule_duplicate_drop` receipt instead of executing again.
- Decision receipts append to `~/.joelclaw/observer-dispatcher-decisions.jsonl` with verb, scheduleId, late flag, pane-created/refusal, planned commands, and shell detail.
- Missing target/brief/loop/prompt paths produce refusal receipts and no pane.
- Pane safety uses split-first, then closes too-small split panes and falls back to a fresh tab, matching the tick script's 80x24 viability lesson.

Planned command examples from test fixtures:

- WAKE: `herdr --session observer agent send w1:p1 "SCHEDULE_WAKE\\nscheduleId: sched-wake\\nlate: true"` then `herdr --session observer pane send-keys w1:p1 enter`.
- SPAWN: `herdr --session observer pane split w1:p2 --direction right --ratio 0.5 --cwd /repo --no-focus`; rename `$PANE` to `⏰ Wake the thing`; run `cd '/repo' && pi @'<briefPath>' "Scheduled SPAWN sched-spawn"`.
- REVIVE: too-small split fixture chooses `herdr --session observer tab create --cwd /repo --label "👁️📡 Observer family — memory loop + dispatcher" --no-focus`; rename `$PANE` to `⏰ Continue useful work`; run `cd '/repo' && pi @'/tmp/sched-revive.md'`.

Verification:

- `bun --check .pi/extensions/dispatcher/lib.ts .pi/extensions/dispatcher/index.ts`
- `bun test` — 75 pass, 0 fail.

Live end-to-end firing remains steering's acceptance gate.
